incolnshire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1563–1616":"1563–1616","1560–Male":"1560–Zesnulý","1565–Female":"1565–Zesnulá","1560–1616":"1560–1616","1583–1628":"1583–1628","1593–Male":"1593–Zesnulý","1524–1588":"1524–1588","1524–Female":"1524–Zesnulá","1583":"1583","1571":"1571","1593":"1593","1560":"1560","13 October 1583":"13. října 1583","17 Mar 1593":"17. března 1593","1569":"1569","abt 1588":"okolo 1588","1524":"1524","1600":"1600","1588":"1588","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1563":"1563","1585":"1585","1628":"1628","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","Chelmsford, Essex, England":"Chelmsford, Essex, Anglie","Essex, England":"Essex, Anglie","Bourne, Lincs, Eng.":"Bourne, Lincolnshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1563–1616":"1563–1616","1560–Male":"1560–Afdød","1565–Female":"1565–Afdød","1560–1616":"1560–1616","1583–1628":"1583–1628","1593–Male":"1593–Afdød","1524–1588":"1524–1588","1524–Female":"1524–Afdød","1583":"1583","1571":"1571","1593":"1593","1560":"1560","13 October 1583":"13. oktober 1583","17 Mar 1593":"17. marts 1593","1569":"1569","abt 1588":"omkring 1588","1524":"1524","1600":"1600","1588":"1588","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1563":"1563","1585":"1585","1628":"1628","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","Chelmsford, Essex, England":"Chelmsford, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Bourne, Lincs, Eng.":"Bourne, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1563–1616":"1563–1616","1560–Male":"1560–Overleden","1565–Female":"1565–Overleden","1560–1616":"1560–1616","1583–1628":"1583–1628","1593–Male":"1593–Overleden","1524–1588":"1524–1588","1524–Female":"1524–Overleden","1583":"1583","1571":"1571","1593":"1593","1560":"1560","13 October 1583":"13 oktober 1583","17 Mar 1593":"17 maart 1593","1569":"1569","abt 1588":"circa 1588","1524":"1524","1600":"1600","1588":"1588","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1563":"1563","1585":"1585","1628":"1628","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","Chelmsford, Essex, England":"Chelmsford, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Bourne, Lincs, Eng.":"Bourne, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1563–1616":"1563–1616","1560–Male":"1560–Deceased","1565–Female":"1565–Deceased","1560–1616":"1560–1616","1583–1628":"1583–1628","1593–Male":"1593–Deceased","1524–1588":"1524–1588","1524–Female":"1524–Deceased","1583":"1583","1571":"1571","1593":"1593","1560":"1560","13 October 1583":"13 October 1583","17 Mar 1593":"17 March 1593","1569":"1569","abt 1588":"about 1588","1524":"1524","1600":"1600","1588":"1588","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1563":"1563","1585":"1585","1628":"1628","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","Chelmsford, Essex, England":"Chelmsford, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Bourne, Lincs, Eng.":"Bourne, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fitch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Old French <i>fiche</i>, perhaps ‘pointed implement for fixing or transfixing something or someone’ (such as a lance?), a derivative of Old French <i>fichier</i> ‘to fix, fasten, pin on, stick into, pierce’. Compare Modern French <i>fiche</i> ‘peg, pin’. Reaney remarks that ‘as Hugh <i>Malet</i> is said to have abandoned for a time his nickname ‘little hammer’ in favor of <i>Fichet</i> (see   Mallet  ), <i>fiche</i> must have been used of a pointed weapon, a spear or lance, and <i>Fitch</i> and <i>Fitchett</i> (see   Fitchett  ) of a spearman or a knight famous for his exploits with the lance’. Use of <i>Fiche</i> as a personal name is possibly implied by diminutive personal name forms such as <i>Fechet</i> (see   Fitchett  ) and <i>Fechel</i>, attested in <i>Fechel</i> de Fercalahn, 1225–50. The latter is perhaps the source of the now extinct English surname <b>Fetchell</b>.","occasionally a variant of   Fitz  .","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Fitchett","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>Fichet</i>, <i>Fichot</i>, or (in northern France) <i>Fiket</i>, <i>Fikot</i>, diminutive forms of <i>fiche</i> or <i>fike</i> ‘pointed implement for fixing or transfixing something or someone’ (such as a spear?), used as a nickname and as a personal name. See   Fitch  ."]},{"name":"Mallet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jean-Yves, Adelard, Alain, Henri, Jacques, Leonce, Lucien, Monique, Philippe.","French: nickname from a diminutive of   Mal   ‘bad’. Alternatively, from a derivative of the related Old French word <i>maleit</i> ‘accursed’ (from Latin <i>maledictus</i>, the opposite of <i>benedictus</i> ‘blessed’), applied as a nickname for an unlucky person. Compare   Malet   1.","French: variant of   Malet   2, an Old French pet form of the personal name   Malo  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":6,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":8,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":22,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":24,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":37,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Fitch was born in 1563, in Chelmsford, Essex, England, her father, Robert Fitch, was 39 and her mother, Ellen Carver, was 39. She had at least 1